From arens Yigal Arens Subject Arrest of fugitive in ADL case Los Angeles Times Saturday May Page FIGURE IN ADL SPY CASE ARRESTED AT AIRPORT ESPIONAGE Former police officer is taken into custody upon arriving from Philippines where he had fled after FBI By Jenifer Warren Times staff writer San Francisco A former San Francisco police officer who fled to the Philippines amid accusations that he funneled confidential law enforcement information to an investigator for the Anti Defamation League was arrested at the airport here on felony charges police said Thomas Gerard who abruptly left the United States in October after the FBI questioned him about his activities was apprehended Thursday night after a source in the Philippines told investigators that Gerard was returning Gerard was booked into San Francisco County Jail early Friday morning on eight counts of theft of government documents and one count each of computer theft burglary and If convicted on all charges Gerard could face years in prison and in Bail was initially set at after police argued that he was a flight risk but it was later reduced to A friend of Gerard was trying to post bail late Friday afternoon a sheriff's spokeswoman Gerard returned to the United because he missed his wife and child with whom he lived on a houseboat in Sausalito and wanted to have his day in court said Police John Willett his former boss and one of two arresting Gerard an undercover agent for the Central Intelligence Agency from to also feared that the CIA was out to kill him Willett In an interview with The Times last month Gerard threatened to disclose illegal CIA support of death squads in Central America if he was indicted and tried on the San Francisco spying Gerard is a central figure in a scandal over an intelligence network operated by the Anti Defamation League a prominent Jewish civil rights Investigators allege that Gerard illegally gave criminal histories to Roy Bullock a San Francisco art dealer who said he has been